{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":3433,"record_hash":"sha256:a59398a92f11fc2c78f6b48c0390398aabe9f0a4c84b3980ba776ccd148b5dc5","timestamp":"2026-05-07T14:54:54.343Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 7ed9a5\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 815\nOutput:\n# Agent Session Capture\n\nThis directory describes a proposed GitButler integration for capturing AI coding\nsession metadata into GitMeta.\n\nThis is still a spec, not an implementation. Treat the documents here as the\ncurrent design target plus a parking lot for ideas that are intentionally out of\nscope for the first proof of concept.\n\nBefore using this as a coding-agent prompt, run it through the review loop in\n[Spec Iteration Process](spec-iteration-process.md). For the first actual patch,\n[First POC Implementation Contract](first-poc-implementation.md) is the source of\ntruth.\n\n## POC Shape\n\nThe first milestone should be deliberately boring and explicit:\n\n- a new Rust crate owns agent session capture behavior\n- the GitButler CLI exposes a hidden, feature-gated command\n- the first implementation captures Codex data from an explicit transcript path\n- provenance/cursor data is written to GitMeta local storage by default\n- raw transcript records are written only with `--include-transcript`\n- no background watcher, broad machine scan, or remote exchange\n- GitMeta serialization and sync/push integration remain future work\n\nA good first command shape is:\n\n```text\nbut agent-session capture \\\n  --agent codex \\\n  --transcript-path <path> \\\n  --target project \\\n  --include-transcript\n```\n\n## Design Bias\n\nPrefer safety and auditability over clever discovery. It is better for the POC\nto capture nothing unless given an exact transcript than to accidentally capture\nthe wrong or private session.\n\n## Documents\n\n- [Spec Iteration Process](spec-iteration-process.md)\n- [First POC Implementation Contract](first-poc-implementation.md)\n- [Requirements and Goals](requirements-and-goals.md)\n- [Architecture](architecture.md)\n- [GitMeta Data Model](gitmeta-data-model.md)\n- [Capture Workflow](capture-workflow.md)\n\n## Reference Material\n\n- [GitMeta specification](https://git-meta.com/spec/)\n- [GitMeta targets and keys](https://git-meta.com/spec/exchange-format/targets.html)\n- [GitMeta list values](https://git-meta.[REDACTED:entropy].html)\n- [GitMeta standard keys](https://git-meta.com/spec/implementation/standard-keys.html)\n- [GitMeta workflow guidance](https://git-meta.com/spec/implementation/workflow.html)\n- Do not infer a branch, commit, or change-id target in the first milestone.\n- Do not write any transcript log unless `--include-transcript` is set; when set,\n  write it under local-only `meta:local:gitbutler:*` keys.\n\n## Initial User Story\n\nA developer has Codex working in a Git repository. After an agent turn completes,\nCodex, a hook, or the user runs:\n\n```text\nbut agent-session capture \\\n  --agent codex \\\n  --transcript-path ~/.codex/sessions/.../session.jsonl \\\n  --target project\n```\n\nGitButler reads that transcript, appends any new records to GitMeta, records\nenough cursor information to avoid duplicate capture next time, and prints a\nreport.\n\nA later milestone can allow:\n\n```text\nbut agent-session capture --agent codex\n```\n\n…but only after exact-input capture, deduplication, and privacy behavior are\nproven.\n\n## Functional Requirements\n\n- The command accepts an explicit agent name.\n- The command requires an explicit transcript/session path in the POC.\n- The command can accept an explicit GitMeta target.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T14:54:54.343Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}